<HEADLINE>
FT  18 MAR 93 / International Company News: Bayer warns on prices as sales
slide
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL ABRAHAMS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LEVERKUSEN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
WORLDWIDE sales of Bayer, the German chemicals giant, fell by 11 per cent in
the first two months of this year, the company said yesterday.
Mr Manfred Schneider, chairman, said there was no prospect of a recovery in
Europe during 1993. He warned that prices worldwide might fall by 1.5 per
cent during the year.
Sales in Germany were down 8 per cent so far this year. In the last quarter
of 1992, pre-tax profits in Bayer's German subsidiary halved.
Worldwide pretax profits for the fourth quarter fell 17 per cent to DM469m,
on sales down 4.4 per cent at DM9.45bn. For the year, group profits fell 16
per cent to DM2.7bn, on turnover down 2.8 per cent. The dividend was cut
from DM13 to DM11 a share.
Bayer's German pre-tax profits for the year were down 27.6 per cent at
DM1.33bn on sales down 3.2 per cent at DM17.5bn.
The decline in turnover was accentuated by the strength of the D-Mark, which
reduced sales by 3 per cent, Mr Schneider said.
Volume growth last year of 1.9 per cent - equivalent to DM800m - was offset
by price falls of nearly 2 per cent. Polymers, organic chemicals and
industrial chemicals registered the largest drop in prices.
Healthcare, which includes pharmaceuticals, non-prescription medicines and
diagnostics, generated operating profits of DM1.82bn. It was the only
division to report an increase in sales - up 1.4 per cent at DM9bn.
Agrochemicals results fell 21 per cent to DM378m, on sales down 3.5 per cent
at DM5.15bn. The polymers division posted a trading loss of DM37m, on
turnover down 7.5 per cent at DM7.2bn.
Industrial products which include polyurethanes and pigments, generated an
operating profit down 34.7 per cent at DM275m on sales down 2.6 per cent at
DM7.6bn. The organic products division reported operating profits down 14.8
per cent at DM121m on sales down 5.1 per cent at DM5.4bn. The sector
suffered from a downturn in the textile sector and increased competition
from Asian groups.
The company is cutting 230 jobs at its Dralon plants at Dormagen, Germany.
</TEXT>
