<HEADLINE>
FT  18 MAR 93 / Spring Ram asks for its shares to be suspended
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JANE FULLER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FEARS about the 1992 results of Spring Ram, the kitchens and bathrooms
company, surfaced yesterday as the group asked for its shares to be
suspended ahead of Monday's scheduled announcement. The fast-growing
company, which seemed to defy the recession, said it would release further
information soon about the 1992 results.
Attention focused on a possible disagreement with the auditors, Arthur
Andersen. The group has in the past brought out its audited annual report on
the same day as the results announcement.
The audit was expected to be particularly thorough after revelations of
false accounting at Spring Ram's Balterley Bathrooms subsidiary last
November. Profits at Balterley had been overstated by Pounds 5.6m mainly
through the inflation of stock values and sales.
The company has since gone to some lengths to reassure them that Balterley
was an isolated incident.
The share price, which had sunk to 89p after the Balterley debacle, was
suspended yesterday at 129p - catching shareholders and analysts by
surprise.
After the suspension, analysts were raising all the questions that were
asked at the time of the Balterley debacle.
The questions include ones about stock valuations and high stock levels, the
timing of sales, depreciation, and the treatment of government grants.
The group's financial and management controls have also been called into
question. There are no non-executive directors.
The Balterley issue was dealt with mainly by finance director Mr Stuart
Greenwood, with chairman and co-founder Mr Bill Rooney coming to London to
reassure institutions.
Until yesterday, analysts were forecasting 1992 pre-tax profits at Pounds
37m-Pounds 40m.
Spring Ram, founded in 1979, became a glamour stock as it built sales to
Pounds 194m and pre-tax profit to Pounds 37.6m in 1991. After flotation in
1983, its market value grew from Pounds 11m to a peak of Pounds 651m last
May.
Lex, Page 24
