<HEADLINE>
FT  18 MAR 93 / Marley declines 67% to Pounds 8m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR, Construction Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE REVIVAL in the UK housing market is starting to boost sales of some
building materials according to Marley, the UK construction products group
which yesterday announced a 67 per cent fall last year in pre-tax profits.
Profits after exceptional provisions of Pounds 10.4m slumped from Pounds 25m
to Pounds 8.1m reflecting the deep recession in the UK construction industry
last year.
UK profits fell from Pounds 10.3m to Pounds 1.2m after a Pounds 2.3m
second-half loss. Up to a third of group sales are generated from the UK
housing market, according to Mr David Trapnell, chief executive.
US profits by comparison almost doubled from Pounds 3.9m to Pounds 7.7m. The
German residential market continues to show little sign of flagging as far
as Marley's products were concerned, said Mr Trapnell. The DIY market in
eastern Germany remained particularly strong and profits in western Europe
rose from Pounds 12.4m to Pounds 12.9m last year.
The group, as forecast, paid a final dividend of 2.1p making a total of 4.2p
for the year compared with 6.35p in 1991. Earnings per share after
exceptional provisions, mostly to cover closure costs and redundancies in
the UK, fell from 6p to 0.7p.
Net borrowings as a percentage of shareholders' funds, following write-downs
and currency movements, rose from 41 per cent to 57 per cent. Marley, in
spite of increased gearing, generated a positive operational cashflow last
year. About 80 per cent of worldwide turnover was from the building
industry, according to Mr Trapnell.
He had been encouraged by an increase in UK sales of plumbing and drainage
products and thermalite blocks during the past four to six weeks. 'I believe
we have seen the bottom of the cycle. Much now will depend upon how UK
housing starts respond to increased demand seen recently from house
purchasers,' he said.
Sales of roof tiles however, remained depressed. Prices of building
materials, where supply was continuing to outrun demand, were likely to
remain under pressure said the Marley chief executive. The group reiterated
its intention to sell its UK brick businesses, where it holds a 2 per cent
market share, should a buyer 'at the right price' be found.
