<HEADLINE>
FT  18 MAR 93 / 'Obsessive' hacker cleared of computer misuse
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MASON, Law Courts Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A SCHOOLBOY whose obsession with computer hacking led him to break into
computers operated by the Financial Times and other institutions was
acquitted yesterday of three charges brought under the Computer Misuse Act.
Mr Paul Bedworth, aged 19, had become so addicted to hacking that he became
ill and no longer knew why he did it, according to expert psychiatric
evidence given at his trial.
In the first prosecution brought under the 1990 Computer Misuse Act, Mr
Bedworth denied charges of conspiracy to obtain telecommunications services
dishonestly, conspiracy to cause unauthorised modification in computer
material and conspiracy to secure unauthorised access to computer material.
The prosecution was regarded as a test of the new law, which was brought in
specifically to outlaw hacking, but the nature of Mr Bedworth's defence
means that questions about the effectiveness of the law remain unanswered.
Mr Bedworth, from Ilkley, Yorkshire, began hacking when he was 14, using a
Pounds 200 BBC microcomputer given to him as a Christmas present, the court
had been told. From his bedroom, he gained entry into computers run by large
organisations and then used their telephone accounts to fund other hacking.
His activities cost The Financial Times more than Pounds 20,000 and the
Brussels-based European Organisation for the Research and Treatment of
Cancer Pounds 10,000 in telephone bills.
However, at his trial at Southwark Crown Court, Professor James Griffith
Edwards, an expert on addictive behaviour, had said Mr Bedworth's obsession
had become so strong that it was impossible to judge what his intentions had
been.
Mr Karl Strickland, 22, from Liverpool, and Mr Neil Woods, 26, from Oldham,
admitted similar conspiracy charges under the Computer Misuse Act before the
trial.
Full report, Page 7
</TEXT>
