<HEADLINE>
FT  17 MAR 93 / Group debates life after Taurus
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MORE THAN 60 represent-atives of custody and registration companies met
yesterday at the offices of Royal Bank of Scotland in the City in an attempt
to agree a joint approach on a successor to the Taurus settlement system.
Some large institutional investors were also present, and the meeting marked
the start of concerted lobbying on the issue.
Custodians and registrars, who provide securities services to large
investors and listed companies, potentially have the most to lose from the
stock-market settlement system chosen in place of Taurus.
The representatives at the meeting agreed to submit a joint proposal to the
Bank of England task force on settlement, under associate director Mr Pen
Kent, by the end of this week. This will recommend that the Bank pushes
ahead with developing an automated settlement system for large institutional
investors.
Also, it will recommend setting up a clearing house to take over the running
of settlement from the Stock Exchange, said Mr Pearson.
A further recommendation will be for a quick move to rolling settlement,
under which all share bargains are settled after a set number of days.
Mr Terry Pearson, head of global custody at Royal Bank of Scotland, said
yesterday's meeting had shown a positive reaction to the Bank of England's
push to find a quick replacement for Taurus. He said the initiative did not
represent an attempt by particular vested interests in the City to protect
their position. Registrars derailed the original Taurus proposal in the late
1980s by opposing the setting up of a central database to hold all records
of shareholdings. It was also considered technically difficult and expensive
to build such a large database, although computing costs have fallen since
then.
Yesterday Mr Pearson said the idea of a central share depository and
registration service remained technically difficult. 'That was kicked into
touch before,' he said. 'It was an impossible task.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
