<HEADLINE>
FT  17 MAR 93 / World Trade News: S Korea to face chip curbs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LIONEL BARBER and LOUISE KEHOE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS, SAN FRANCISCO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE European Commission and the US Commerce Department both acted yesterday
to prevent dumping of South Korean-built semiconductor memory chips.
In both cases, Korean chip manufacturers were found to have sold Dynamic
Random Access Memory (Dram) chips below fair value. In the US, dumping
duties were set at 0.74 per cent to 7.19 per cent with Hyundai facing the
highest duties.
The EC, however, has secured an agreement on minimum prices from the three
leading Korean manufacturers of Dram chips, heading off the threat of
extended anti-dumping duties. Goldstar, Hyundai and Samsung have offered
undertakings on future minimum prices as part of a new self-policing Korean
producers' regime on memory chips, similar to an EC arrangement with
Japanese producers. Other Korean producers face anti-dumping duties of 24.7
per cent.
Korean industry and trade officials had tried to secure a similar
arrangement with the US but were rebuffed. However, the final dumping duties
determined by the Commerce Department are far lower than its original
estimates, which had ranged from 6 to 87 per cent.
</TEXT>
