<HEADLINE>
FT  17 MAR 93 / The Budget: Confusion over changes to BES
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE abolition of Business Expansion Schemes involving loans threw the tax
shelter market into confusion.
Loan-backed schemes were introduced for the first time last September, and
since then have raised Pounds 568m, according to the BES Association.
However, they came in for strong criticism because their structure allowed
hefty profits for top-rate taxpayers without allowing basic rate taxpayers
to make any return at all. As one accountant put it, they allowed top-rate
taxpayers to convert themselves into basic rate payers.
Demand for the schemes was exceptional - Mr Charles Fry, chairman of Johnson
Fry, the largest BES sponsor, claims to have received Pounds 84m for the
schemes since last Friday.
Around Pounds 850m has been raised by all BES companies so far this tax
year, according to the Allenbridge Group, a BES intermediary, compared to
Pounds 407m in 1991-92.
The Building Societies Association said that schemes without loans 'may
still have a contribution to make', although removing loans makes the
schemes less attractive for lenders.
</TEXT>
