<HEADLINE>
FT  17 MAR 93 / The Budget: Promises betrayed, says Labour
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY, DAVID OWEN and IVOR OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
'We have no plans and no need to raise extra resources from value added tax'
John Major, March 1992
'We do not see any need to increase the tax burden'
John Major, March 1992
'We will maintain martgage tax relief'
Conservative party general election manifesto
MR JOHN SMITH, the Labour leader, yesterday accused the government of having
'cynically and ruthlessly betrayed' its election pledges not to raise tax or
VAT.
In a vigorous first reaction to the chancellor's speech, he personally
targetted Mr John Major by repeating a number of statements made by the
prime minister in the run-up to last year's election.
To angry shouts of 'cheats' from the Labour benches and silence from the
Tories, Mr Smith quoted Mr Major's insistence that the Conservatives would
not raise or extend the range of value added tax.
'I don't know how the prime minister can sit there as leader of a government
capable of deceit on such a scale,' he said to roars of approval. 'These
people make pledges as if they matter not a whit.'
Mr Smith went on to single out the increase in national insurance
contributions as particularly iniquitous, claiming it was worse than a rise
in income tax 'as it affects the people further down the scale'.
And he went on to point out that the imposition of VAT on domestic energy
bills would hit millions of badly-off people who would not qualify for the
exemptions offered to those on income support.
The extension of the 20p tax band by a further Pounds 500 would have little
impact, Mr Smith claimed, while part of it was already lost by the decision
not to raise tax allowances in line with inflation.
The measures to tackle unemployment were grossly inadequate and would help
just a third of the 300,000 who had lost their jobs since the election, he
said.
Later, Mr Gordon Brown, the shadow chancellor, described the Budget as
amounting to a Pounds 17.5bn tax increase over the next three years and 'the
biggest tax rise in history'.
Mr Brown said that the average family's tax bill would go up by Pounds 8 a
week when fuel costs, national insurance contributions, married couples'
allowances and excise duties were taken into account. He went on to promise
that Labour would campaign against the Budget across the country on the
theme of 'The Betrayal of Britain'.
Mr Smith's attack was echoed by other opposition parties. Mr Malcolm Bruce,
the Liberal Democrat trade and industry spokesman, described the Budget was
one of of 'despair - even a Budget of desperation'.
He criticised the 'totally appalling' phasing-in of the full rate of VAT on
domestic fuel, and said it was also a 'desperately disappointing' Budget for
the unemployed.
Mr Alex Salmond, the Scottish National party leader, said it was a 'bankrupt
Budget from a bankrupt chancellor . . . the myth of the low-tax Tories has
finally been destroyed.'
Even on the Tory benches, there was an early display of unease. Mr John
Biffen, MP for Shropshire north, a former Treasury minister, questioned
whether the whether proposed tax increases were adequate to deal with a
public sector borrowing requirement expected to reach Pounds 50bn in
1993-94.
