<HEADLINE>
FT  17 MAR 93 / The Budget: Horse traders clear a hurdle
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JANE FULLER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FEARS that leading racehorse owners and premier bloodstock auctions would
leave the UK, jeopardising the industry, have been lifted by VAT changes.
Allowing racehorse owners to claim back the VAT they pay on buying and
running their horses will remove the disadvantage of operating in the UK,
compared with the Repubic of Ireland with its 2.5 per cent rate and France
with 5.5 per cent.
Owners considering moving their strings abroad included the Maktoum family
of Dubai and the American Mr Paul Mellon. They and about 8,000 others will
be able to reclaim VAT on the Pounds 12,000-plus annual expense of running a
racehorse as well as on purchase prices.
Tattersalls, the leading auction house, yesterday indicated it would reverse
the switching of activities to Ireland. Average selling price at its premier
yearling sale is 35,000 to 50,000 guineas.
The industry had estimated that 30,000 jobs were at risk at racing yards and
studs and among vets, blacksmiths and horse transporters.
Mr Gerald Leigh, a Northamptonshire breeder, said he had been selling his
yearlings abroad and would have considered running down his establishment
from 10 staff to three.
Mr Peter Walwyn, a trainer at Lambourn, said he had lost clients to overseas
trainers. Custom had also been reduced by the weight of VAT. 'We will now
keep the clients we have and get more in.'
To enable the changes to go ahead, the Jockey Club will remove barriers to
horse sponsorship and appearance money.
</TEXT>
