<HEADLINE>
FT  17 MAR 93 / The Budget (Government Statements): Reforms aim to boost
North Sea - Oil Resources
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
This section contains details of the government's planned tax changes which
were given in separate announcements from the Inland Revenue, Customs and
Excise and other government departments after the chancellor had made his
publication of the Budget details in the Finance Bill.
REFORM of the North Sea oil taxation regime was announced, with the
objective of encouraging further development of oil and gas resources 'by
allowing companies to keep more of the fruits of their efforts,' the
chancellor said.
The Treasury said the main proposals were:
to reduce the rate of petroleum revenue tax (PRT), which is charged on UK
oil and gas production, from 75 per cent to 50 per cent;
to abolish PRT on oil and gas fields given development consent on or after
Budget day;
to abolish, subject to transitional arrangements, PRT rules that allow
expenditure on new exploration and development to be set against profits of
existing fields;
to make other technical improvements to North Sea taxation.
The rate of PRT on existing fields will be reduced from 75 per cent to 50
per cent for six-month chargeable periods ending after 30 June 1993. PRT is
to be completely abolished for future 'non-taxable' fields. 'Non-taxable'
fields are those given development consent by the Department of Trade and
Industry on or after March 16 1993.
The abolition applies to tariffing income from third-party use of assets and
disposal receipts from asset sales as well as to oil and gas production
income.
Cross-field PRT relief for exploration and appraisal (E&amp;A) - setting the
cost of E&amp;A for a new field against the PRT profits of an existing field -
is to be abolished. This will apply to expenditure incurred on or after
March 16 1993 except where the expenditure was both necessarily incurred
under contracts signed before Budget day and incurred within two years after
Budget day.
Cross-field allowance (CFA) - setting up to 10 per cent of the cost of
developing a new field against the PRT profits of an existing field - is to
be unchanged for 'taxable fields', that is, fields with development consent
before Budget day: and is to be abolished for 'non-taxable' fields outside
PRT
Tariff receipts allowance (TRA) is to be unchanged for tariffs paid by
'taxable' fields. Where a future, 'non-taxable', field pays a tariff, no TRA
will be due in the service-providing field.
Oil allowance is to be unchanged, as is 'ring fence' corporation tax
(subject to Budget measures applying to all companies). Thus, for example,
100 per cent E&amp;A relief is effectively maintained at corporation tax rates.
Measures will be introduced to ensure that future expenditure does not get
relieved early, and thus at a higher PRT rate than justified.
The rules on when expenditure is 'incurred' for PRT purposes, including in
transactions between associates, will be clarified. Expenditure will be
treated as 'incurred' only when the claimant has an unconditional obligation
to pay another party the amount claimed.
Rules will allow stage payments to be claimed, provided they are not
disproportionate to the performance of the contract at that time. The rules
on when expenditure may be allowed in a PRT assessment will also be
clarified. Expenditure incurred after the end of a chargeable period will
not be allowed (other than by carry-back of future losses) in a PRT
assessment in respect of that period.
Where losses are carried back against PRT paid in earlier chargeable
periods, the PRT repayment plus interest is now 'capped' at 85 per cent of
the part of the loss carried back to the earlier period.
With the PRT rate reduced from 75 per cent to 50 per cent, the 'cap' is
similarly to be reduced from 85 per cent to 60 per cent. This will apply to
repayments in respect of chargeable periods ending after June 30 1993, ie
after the rate cut.
Where losses are carried back to periods pre-dating the rate cut, the
present 85 per cent cap will continue to apply to the repayments for those
periods.
Fields (or parts of fields) not within UK jurisdiction come into the PRT
charge only in respect of tariff or disposal receipts.
In line with the treatment of future UK-sector fields, future 'foreign
fields' will be 'non-taxable' fields, ie outside PRT. Fields straddling an
international boundary line will be treated as wholly 'non-taxable' fields
where the UK part is 'non-taxable'.
</TEXT>
<XX>
