<HEADLINE>
FT  17 MAR 93 / The Budget (Government Statements): Standard set for excise
payments - Oil Duty
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
This section contains details of the government's planned tax changes which
were given in separate announcements from the Inland Revenue, Customs and
Excise and other government departments after the chancellor had made his
publication of the Budget details in the Finance Bill.
EXCISE DUTY on oil is to be assessed in future on the volume of the oil at a
standard 15 degrees Celsius, Customs and Excise said yesterday.
Customs described the change as technical, required to implement the
provisions of an EC directive on the duty structure for mineral oils.
It said: 'The density of oil products varies with temperature and the actual
quantity of oil delivered will vary slightly as the temperature rises and
falls.
The proposal will require deliveries of oil products to be adjusted to the
volume which would have been delivered at a temperature of 15 degrees
Celsius and the excise duty calculated on that volume.
'As our climate does not suffer from wide extremes of temperature and the
adjustments are in any case very small, this proposal will have only a minor
impact. Domestic consumers will notice no change.
'This system is already widely used by oil companies for internal
accounting, and is the agreed method of duty accounting in the EC.
'At present excise duty is accounted for on the basis of the volume at the
delivered temperature. Conversion to a standard temperature ensures that any
difference is cor-rected and that a consistent quantity of product is
accounted for.'
The Finance Bill will make provision for the conversion methods to be used,
and for retaining bulk volume measurement in circumstances where temperature
adjustment is not possible (eg importation of oil in drums).
A joint Customs/Industry Working Group has been formed to produce guidelines
on the introduction and operation of standard temperature accounting.
Subject to the recommendations of this group, the change is expected to take
effect on 15 October 1993. This coincides with the start of a duty
accounting period.
The proposal is expected to be revenue neutral.
</TEXT>
