<HEADLINE>
FT  17 MAR 93 / The Budget (Government Statements): Definition of beer and
some wines to widen - Excise duties
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
This section contains details of the government's planned tax changes which
were given in separate announcements from the Inland Revenue, Customs and
Excise and other government departments after the chancellor had made his
publication of the Budget details in the Finance Bill.
AN EXTENSION of the definitions of beer and sparkling wine is among measures
proposed to comply with European single market rules on excise duties.
The definition of beer will be extended to cover all beer exceeding 0.5 per
cent alcohol by volume (ABV) and any product containing a mixture of beer
with non-alcoholic drinks, Customs and Excise said.
However, for beer between 0.5 per cent and 1.2 per cent ABV no duty will be
payable. All movements of beer within the EC, whatever strength, will be
governed by the same control arrangements.
The definition of sparkling wine will be extended to include wine in any
bottle having a mushroom stopper held in place by ties or fastenings,
regardless of the pressure. Previously, wine in mushroom stopper bottles was
not dutied as sparkling wine if the pressure was below 1.5 bars. No known
current products are affected.
The limit up to which wine and made-wine may be strengthened by adding
additional alcohol will be set at 22 per cent ABV. This proposal aligns the
fortification levels for wine and made-wine. Previously it had been
permissible for wine to be strengthened up to 23 per cent ABV but no known
current products are affected.
The blending or mixing of alcoholic products to produce a dutiable alcoholic
product for sale is being restricted to taking place within premises
approved as tax warehouses, unless Customs directs otherwise. The effect is
to ensure that the correct rate of duty is paid on the finished product.
This measure does not extend to drinks mixed at the point of sale, such as
cocktails in pubs or cocktail bars.
Wine and made-wine with a strength of more than 22 per cent ABV will be
dutied at the same rate per degree of alcohol as spirits.
The definition of methylated spirits, which are exempt from excise duty,
will be extended to include spirits denatured to other member states'
requirements, provided they have EC approval.
With the exception of the change to duty payable on alcoholic drinks with a
strength over 22 per cent (which takes effect from Budget day) all other
provisions take effect from royal assent.
The beer end-product duty rate will be Pounds 10.45 per hectolitre per one
per cent of alcohol by volume when the new system is brought into effect on
June 1 1993.
The chancellor also proposed to repeal the provisions allowing drawback
(refund of duty) on beer deposited in an excise warehouse. The repeal will
come into effect on September 1 1993. With the introduction of beer
end-product duty, these provisions are no longer necessary as it will be
possible for beer to move to an excise warehouse without payment of excise
duty.
It is intended to repeal the existing drawback (refund of duty) arrangements
for beer going to the Isle of Man. The provisions will be brought into
effect when agreement is reached between the UK and Isle of Man governments
on making beer duty a shared revenue.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9311 Finance, Taxation, and Monetary Policy.
    P2082 Malt Beverages.
    P2084 Wines, Brandy and Brandy Spirits.
    P2085 Distilled and Blended Liquors.
