<HEADLINE>
FT  17 MAR 93 / The Budget (Government Statements): Revenue-neutral tax
measures - Lloyd's Underwriters
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
This section contains details of the government's planned tax changes which
were given in separate announcements from the Inland Revenue, Customs and
Excise and other government departments after the chancellor had made his
publication of the Budget details in the Finance Bill.
THE chancellor proposed in his Budget to introduce a package of measures to
reform the tax arrangements applying to Lloyd's underwriters. Overall the
reform is revenue-neutral. The main features are:
A new tax deductible reserve, replacing the present limited special reserve
fund, to enable underwriters to put aside profits free of tax to meet future
losses.
Removing the special treatment of gains on assets representing invested
premiums and incorporating them in trading profits.
A more coherent and comprehensive set of rules for taxing receipts and
giving relief for various expenses.
The chancellor's intention is to help underwriters build up reserves to meet
future losses and to simplify and rationalise the present system of taxing
underwriters.
The chancellor proposed in his Budget to introduce a power to make
regulations about the timing of repayments to friendly societies which have
some tax-exempt business.
The chancellor's intention is that the present concessional arrangements
under which these societies receive repayments of tax should be replaced by
a statutory scheme coming into effect on January 1 1994.
It is proposed that the new repayment arrangements will be based on the
existing rules for repaying income tax to both friendly societies and life
assurance companies in respect of their pension business. The new provision
will allow regulations to be made to adapt the pension business rules to the
circumstances of friendly societies with some tax-exempt business.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9311 Finance, Taxation, and Monetary Policy.
    P6411 Insurance Agents, Brokers, and Service.
</IN>
