<HEADLINE>
FT  17 MAR 93 / The Budget (Government Statements): Disincentive removed
over foreigners - Relocation Packages
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
This section contains details of the government's planned tax changes which
were given in separate announcements from the Inland Revenue, Customs and
Excise and other government departments after the chancellor had made his
publication of the Budget details in the Finance Bill.
PROPOSALS TO change the tax treatment of relocation packages offered to
employees who make job-related house moves will remove a disincentive for
companies to bring foreign nationals to work in the UK and reduce the cost
of what had become a very expensive relief, the Treasury said yesterday.
It said there would be two changes.
Tax relief for removal expenses and benefits will be put on to a statutory
basis and limited to Pounds 8,000 per move. Relief will be available whether
or not an employee sells his or her old home.
Tax relief for additional housing cost payments will be withdrawn.
The changes will apply to employees who start a new job or move with their
existing employer on or after April 6 1993, but there will be transitional
arrangements for employees who are already committed to moving.
The existing extra-statutory reliefs will be available for employees who
start new jobs before April 6 1993.
Under the terms of extra-statutory concession A5 an employee is not taxed on
certain removal expenses which an employer pays or re-imburses or on certain
benefits which an employer provides if the employee has to change residence
either as a result of a job transfer with the existing employer or to take
up a new employment.
Relief is available only where it would be unreasonable to expect the
employee to work at the new location without moving nearer to it and
provided the employee disposes of any interest in his or her home at the old
location.
The Inland Revenue interprets 'change of residence' as meaning that the
employee must sell his or her old home.
The chancellor proposed that these conditions should be broadly matched in
the statutory relief.
But there will be some important changes.
There will be a ceiling of Pounds 8,000 on the relief available to set
against the costs of each move.
Employees will no longer be required to sell their old home to qualify for
relief.
Payments by employers to compensate employees for losses on sale of their
old homes will not qualify for relief.
The categories of help given by employers to employees who move house which
will be covered by the proposed statutory relief include:
Selling the old home - for example, legal fees and estate agent services.
Buying or renting the new home - for example, legal fees and stamp duty.
Removal of furniture and effects; assistance with travel and subsistence
costs incurred in connection with the move, for example, journeys undertaken
to find a home at the new location and the provision of temporary
accommodation at the new location before a permanent move. Provision of
replacement goods, services and facilities  - for example, the replacement
of carpets and curtains which are not suitable for removal to the new home.
Bridging loans; and services of relocation management (or similar)
companies.
The new rules will apply to moves relating to jobs started on or after 6
April 1993.
Under transitional arrangements, payments made and benefits provided on or
after April 6 will continue to qualify for extra-statutory tax relief
provided the employee has entered into a firm commitment to move before
April 6 and starts the job at the new location before August 1.
To determine whether an employee satisfies the first condition, the Inland
Revenue will need evidence either that the employer has given formal
notification of the job transfer or that the employee is committed to
accepting the job transfer.
Extra-statutory concession A67 exempts from tax certain payments to
employees by employers towards the additional housing costs - increased
mortgage interest or rent - incurred as a result of moving with their jobs
to more expensive housing areas.
Tax relief is available only when payments are made for a limited period,
reduce year by year and do not in total exceed a prescribed maximum.
The maximum has varied from time to time in line with changes to the amount
payable to civil servants under their additional housing costs allowance.
The present maximum, which has applied since February 1, is Pounds 13,440.
At the chancellor's request, the Board of Inland Revenue will withdraw this
extra-statutory concession with effect from April 6.
Under transitional arrangements tax relief will continue for any employees
who have entered into a firm commitment to move with their jobs to a more
expensive housing area before April 6 and who then start their job at the
new location before August 1.
</TEXT>
