<HEADLINE>
FT  17 MAR 93 / The Budget (Government Statements): Price-based tax aims to
end market distortion - Company Cars
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
This section contains details of the government's planned tax changes which
were given in separate announcements from the Inland Revenue, Customs and
Excise and other government departments after the chancellor had made his
publication of the Budget details in the Finance Bill.
TAXING company cars on the basis of their list price would provide a 'fairer
measure of the benefit people receive, eliminate a cause of distortions in
the new car market, and reduce incentives to drive less fuel-efficient
cars,' the Treasury said yesterday.
It said that company car drivers with relatively cheap cars will be better
off compared with the present system; those with relatively expensive cars
for the band will have a higher tax charge; and those with cars around the
average price for the band will remain in much the same position.
The Treasury said: 'The new system will also deal more neutrally with diesel
cars which often have larger engines than the equivalent petrol car.
'The present broad-scale charges will be replaced by a new measure of the
benefit of a car for private use:
the full cost of the car - 35 per cent of the list price of the car from
April 6 1994;
with a discount of one-third if the employee drives more than 2,500 business
miles in a year, or two-thirds if the employee drives 18,000 or more
business miles;
all reduced by a third for cars four or more years old at the end of the tax
year.
'The effect is that on average the charge will be the same as under the
present system, but some individuals will pay more and others less.
'The chancellor announced in his Budget in 1992 his intention to introduce
price-based measures of the value of company cars. These proposals take
account of views expressed in response to the Inland Revenue's consultative
document issued in July 1992 on the details and timing of the change. The
chancellor proposes to base the new tax charge on the full cost of a car for
a year. Full cost includes not only running costs but also large fixed costs
(such as depreciation and financing costs). The measure of full costs for
the income tax charge will be 35 per cent of the price of the car. Free fuel
for private use will continue to be taxed separately.
'The price of the car will be defined to be its list price at the time it
was first registered, plus the price of 'extras' provided with the car. The
consultative document discussed the operational attractions of some form of
banding of cars by price. After taking into account the views expressed
during the consultative exercise the new system now proposed will not be
banded. Each company car will be dealt with on the basis of its price.
'There will be special rules to arrive at a price for a car if,
exceptionally, no list price is published. In addition cars over 15 years
old, with an open market value of more than Pounds 15,000, will be taxed by
reference to their value if that is higher than their list price.
'The value of the benefit will be reduced to take account of the business
use. The full cost will be reduced by:
one third for 2,500 to 17,999 business miles a year;
two-thirds for 18,000 or more business miles a year.
'This reproduces the present broad apportionment of the costs of a car
between employer and employee which the government indicated last year it
had no plans to change.
'There will also continue to be a further reduction of one third for cars
that are four or more years old at the end of the tax year. Second cars will
also be taxed on their full cost. As at present, there will be no reduction
for business use unless the second car is used for more than 18,000 business
miles a year. The full cost will then be reduced by a third.
'Payments by employees for the private use of the car will continue to
reduce pound for pound the value of the benefit.
'The new system will start on April 6 1994. It will apply in 1994-95 and
subsequent years to all company cars. This timetable will allow the Inland
Revenue to seek, during 1993, details from employers of the prices of the
cars they make available to their employees. The new charges will then be
taken into account at the end of 1993 when setting employees' PAYE codes for
1994-95.
'Neither employees nor employers need contact their tax office about these
changes. The Inland Revenue will get in touch with employers to seek
information about the list prices of their company cars.
'The consultative document proposed new arrangements for employers to notify
the tax office at the end of each month of details of cars newly provided to
employees. It is now proposed that employers should be required to give tax
offices this information only quarterly. This will meet their requests for
less onerous arrangements while still allowing the Inland Revenue to adjust
employees' PAYE codes, and so avoid large underpayments of tax.
'The Inland Revenue will also, with ministers' approval, continue
discussions with employers and other interested parties about the collection
of tax on company cars and possible further ways to simplify administration.
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
