<HEADLINE>
FT  17 MAR 93 / The Budget (Government Statements): Relief for higher-rate
taxpayers to be cut - Married Couple's Allowance
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
This section contains details of the government's planned tax changes which
were given in separate announcements from the Inland Revenue, Customs and
Excise and other government departments after the chancellor had made his
publication of the Budget details in the Finance Bill.
THE chancellor proposes to introduce legislation in the 1994 Finance Bill to
restrict relief for the married couple's allowance, and the other allowances
linked to it, to the lower rate of 20 per cent from 6 April 1994; raise the
married couple's allowance for couples aged 65 and over by Pounds 200; and
increase the width of the lower rate band by another Pounds 500.
The chancellor's intention in restricting the married couple's allowance is
to raise revenue and to make the allowance worth the same amount to
taxpayers at all levels of income.
The married couple's allowance, like the other income tax allowances,
currently reduces a taxpayer's liability at his or her marginal rate of tax.
For example, the current allowance of Pounds 1,720 for someone aged under 65
reduces their annual tax bill by Pounds 688 (40 per cent of Pounds 1,720) if
they are a higher rate taxpayer, but by half that amount (Pounds 344 or 20
per cent of Pounds 1,720) if they pay tax only at the 20 per cent lower
rate.
The change proposed will mean that the allowance will reduce the tax bills
of all taxpayers entitled to it by the same amount, ie 20 per cent of the
allowance. So at the 1993-94 level the allowance for those aged under 65
would be worth Pounds 344 regardless of the taxpayer's marginal rate.
The restriction will also apply to the allowances which are set at the same
level as the married couple's allowance for those aged under 65. For
example: the additional personal allowance (mainly for single parents); the
widow's bereavement allowance (paid to a widow in the year of her husband's
death and the following year); and the relief for maintenance payments to a
divorced or separated spouse.
The widening of the lower rate band will be worth a further Pounds 25 a year
to all basic and higher rate taxpayers, married or single. The net effect of
both measures on a married man aged under 65, paying tax at the basic rate,
and assuming no other changes in allowances, would be a tax increase of
Pounds 1.17 a week. A higher rate taxpayer aged under 65 would pay Pounds
6.13 a week more. Taxpayers with income of less than about Pounds 6,500
would not be affected.
The higher amounts of the MCA for taxpayers aged 65 and over will also be
restricted to 20 per cent, but these allowances will be increased at the
same time so that the maximum loss to a basic rate taxpayer aged 65 or over
will be no greater than the loss to a basic rate taxpayer aged under 65. The
increase in the higher amounts of MCA will mean that about 130,000 taxpayers
on low incomes will gain up to 75 pence a week, including 30,000 who will be
taken out of tax altogether.
The restriction of the value of the married couple's allowance and linked
allowances will be implemented for employees by making a reduction in their
PAYE tax codes.
The amount of the reduction will depend on their marginal rate of tax and
hence on an estimate of their total income. This will be corrected if it
proves to be wrong at the end of the year. Codes including these
restrictions will be issued early in 1994. For taxpayers not covered by
PAYE, the restriction in relief will be made in assessments or in
calculating repayments.
The restriction of the married couple's allowance will raise about Pounds
900m in 1994-95 (Pounds 1.2bn in a full year), of which Pounds 320m in
1994-95 will be spent on increasing the lower rate band to Pounds 3,000.
</TEXT>
