<HEADLINE>
FT  17 MAR 93 / The Budget (Government Statements): Help given over sale of
business assets - Capital Allowance Provisions
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
This section contains details of the government's planned tax changes which
were given in separate announcements from the Inland Revenue, Customs and
Excise and other government departments after the chancellor had made his
publication of the Budget details in the Finance Bill.
CHANGES were announced in capital allowances which allow connected persons
to elect to treat the sale of industrial buildings, and some other business
assets, as having taken place at their tax written-down value.
The changes are aimed at helping some taxpayers wishing to restructure their
business and at preventing manipulation of election provisions. The changes,
in relation to sales on or after 16 March, are:
To extend the provisions to include qualifying hotels; commercial buildings
in enterprise zones; and scientific research assets.
To allow elections only in cases where both parties are entitled to capital
allowances.
The Inland Revenue said: 'Under the capital allowances legislation connected
persons can elect to treat the sale of certain categories of assets, for
example industrial buildings and mineral extraction assets, as having taken
place at tax written-down value (the original cost less allowances already
taken).
The result of this is that the sale will not give rise to any balancing
adjustment. That is, the sale takes place on a no-gain, no-loss basis. In
these cases, writing-down allowances are available to the new owner on the
remaining unrelieved expenditure. Any subsequent disposal of the asset to an
unconnected person will give rise to a charge or allowance on the same basis
as it would have done had the seller continued to own the asset.
Effectively, for capital allowances purposes the buyer 'steps into the
shoes' of the seller.
An election to treat the sale of assets as having taken place at tax
written-down value has previously been unavailable where the assets
concerned were qualifying hotels, commercial buildings in enterprise zones
and scientific research assets. The chancellor's proposal extends the
election provisions to cover such assets.
The chancellor also proposes that no election will be available where
allowances or charges under the Capital Allowances Code cannot be made on
either of the parties to the sale.
This is on the basis that tax-exempt persons cannot 'stand in the shoes' of
taxpayers as far as tax liabilities are concerned.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
