<HEADLINE>
FT  17 MAR 93 / The Budget (Government Statements): Cash flow benefit of up
to Pounds 2bn sought - Taxation of dividends
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
This section contains details of the government's planned tax changes which
were given in separate announcements from the Inland Revenue, Customs and
Excise and other government departments after the chancellor had made his
publication of the Budget details in the Finance Bill.
FIVE linked changes are proposed in the taxation of dividends. The Treasury
said the intention was to provide an overall cash flow benefit of nearly
Pounds 2bn in 1993-94 and 1994-95 to all UK companies paying dividends, to
reduce the amount of new surplus advance corporation tax arising in 1993-94
and subsequent years by some Pounds 300m and to raise revenue of about
Pounds 1,000m a year from 1995-96 onwards.
The main changes are:
to reduce the value of the tax credit on dividends paid by UK companies from
25 per cent to 20 per cent for dividends paid after 5 April 1993;
to reduce correspondingly the present income tax charge on dividends from
the basic rate of 25 per cent to the lower rate of 20 per cent;
to reduce correspondingly the rate at which a UK company has to account for
advance corporation tax (ACT) when it pays a dividend from 25 per cent to 20
per cent, but with a transitional rate for 1993-94 only of 22.5 per cent;
to reduce the rate of corporation tax paid by authorised unit trusts in line
with these changes;
to introduce transitional payments to charities with dividend income from UK
companies.
The general rules are:
Tax credits on dividends: Tax credits accompany dividends paid by UK
companies. They can be set against a UK resident shareholder's liability to
tax on the dividend. A shareholder who is exempt from tax on dividends (such
as a pension fund or a charity), who is not liable to income tax because any
income is covered by allowances, or whose income falls within the lower rate
band of income tax, can claim payment of all or part of the credit. Tax
credits are also payable to certain non-resident shareholders, such as
Commonwealth citizens and citizens of the Republic of Ireland. Partial tax
credits are payable to some other non-resident shareholders under the terms
of some of the UK's double taxation agreements.
The value of the tax credit is currently 25 per cent of the dividend plus
the tax credit. The credit on a dividend of Pounds 75, for example, is
Pounds 25 (25 per cent of Pounds 75 plus Pounds 25). This exactly matches
liability at the basic rate of income tax of 25 per cent on the sum of the
dividend and the tax credit.
From 1993-94, the value of the tax credit falls to 20 per cent of the
dividend plus the tax credit. The credit on a dividend of Pounds 75, for
example, thus becomes Pounds 18.75 (20 per cent of Pounds 75 plus Pounds
18.75). This will exactly match the new income tax charge at the lower rate
on the sum of the dividend and the tax credit.
Tax liability on dividends: Shareholders who are exempt from tax on
dividends, or not liable to tax, will be paid the tax credit on dividends
paid after 5 April 1993 at the lower rate of 20 per cent. This will also
apply to tax credits paid to holders of Personal Equity Plans.
Individual shareholders whose income falls within the lower rate band of
income tax charged at 20 per cent can, at present, claim payment of that
part of the credit which exceeds their liability. After 5 April 1993, they
will not be entitled to any tax credit payment as the tax credit will no
longer exceed the liability.
For shareholders who are currently liable at the basic rate of income tax of
25 per cent, the present tax credit matches the liability on dividends and
there is no further tax to pay. After 5 April 1993, the tax credit will
continue to match the liability exactly, but at 20 per cent.
Individual shareholders who are liable at the higher rate of income tax of
40 per cent currently pay extra tax on dividends at the difference between
the higher rate and the value of the credit. Such a shareholder who at
present receives a dividend of Pounds 75, for example, is taxable at 40 per
cent on income of Pounds 100 (including the tax credit of Pounds 25), and
can set the tax credit of Pounds 25 against the liability of Pounds 40
leaving a further Pounds 15 to pay. For dividends paid after 5 April 1993,
this further payment will be greater. A shareholder receiving a dividend of
Pounds 75, for example, will be taxable at 40 per cent on income of Pounds
93.75 (dividend of Pounds 75 plus tax credit, at the new rate, of Pounds
18,75) and, after setting off the tax credit of Pounds 18.75 against the
liability of Pounds 37.50, there will be a further Pounds 18.75 to pay.
Dividends and other income and allowances: Dividends will be treated as the
top slice of income. A shareholder with income other than dividends will
have the full amount of the lower rate band of 20 per cent available to set
against that other income. A shareholder liable at the higher rate will pay
an additional 20 per cent tax on dividends to the extent that those
dividends fall above the threshold for the higher rate (basic rate limit).
Personal allowances and other reliefs which are set against the total income
of an individual will continue to be given in the way which produces the
greatest reduction in the individual's liability to tax.
Rate of Act: A company which pays a dividend has to pay ACT. The rate at
which ACT is paid is currently 25 per cent of the sum of the dividend and
the ACT payable on it. A company pays ACT of Pounds 25 for each Pounds 75 of
the dividend. After 5 April 1994, the ACT rate will be reduced to 20 per
cent. A company will pay ACT of Pounds 18.75 for each Pounds 75 of the
dividend.
For dividends paid after 5 April 1993 and before 6 April 1994, the ACT rate
will be set between the present and the new rate. It will be 22.5 per cent
of the sum of the dividend and the ACT payable on it. A company will pay ACT
of just over Pounds 21.77 for each Pounds 75 of the dividend.
Other ACT points: The rules for setting ACT against corporation tax
liability will be unchanged.
The maximum amount which a company is able to set against the liability for
any accounting period is the amount of ACT which would have been payable on
a distribution of an amount which, together with the ACT that would have
been payable on it, would have been equal to the profits of the accounting
period. That limit, which at present is Pounds 25 for every Pounds 100 of
taxable profits, will be Pounds 20 for every Pounds 100 of taxable profits
except for the transitional year of 1993-94 when it will be Pounds 22.50.
There are special rules about the ACT payable when a company receives
dividends as a shareholder in another company which it then pays on as
dividends to its own shareholders. Broadly speaking, a company pays ACT only
on the excess of the dividends it pays over the dividends it receives in any
accounting period. Under the proposals, this principle will continue to
apply. For 1993 and 1994, as for any year in which the ACT rate changes, a
company's accounting period which starts before 6 April and finishes on or
after that date will be treated as two separate accounting periods for the
purpose of these rules.
Charities receiving dividends from UK companies are normally entitled to
claim payment of the accompanying tax credit by virtue of their exemption
from tax on this income. For a transitional period of four years from
1993-94, charities will also be able to claim additional payments.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
