<HEADLINE>
FT  17 MAR 93 / The Budget (Government Statements): Exchange gains and
losses
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
This section contains details of the government's planned tax changes which
were given in separate announcements from the Inland Revenue, Customs and
Excise and other government departments after the chancellor had made his
publication of the Budget details in the Finance Bill.
FOREIGN exchange gains and losses for companies on all monetary assets and
liabilities are to be taxed or relieved as income as they accrue, in what
the Chancellor described as a measure to enhance London's status as a world
financial centre.
Exchange gains and losses on monetary assets (such as cash, bank deposits
and debts receivable) and liabilities will be taxed or relieved as income
receipts or deductions (for trading items, as part of trading profits or
losses).
Monetary assets in foreign currency which are currently subject to capital
gains tax will cease to be so.
Exchange differences on monetary items will be recognised as they accrue (as
happens for accounts purposes when the items are translated into sterling).
Unrealised exchange gains above certain limits may be partially deferred
(where they arise on long-term capital items).
Trading profits before capital allowances may be calculated by reference to
currencies other than sterling where certain conditions are met.
There will be provision for exchange differences on a borrowing which
'matches' a non-monetary asset to be deferred until the asset is disposed
of.
</TEXT>
