<HEADLINE>
FT  17 MAR 93 / The Budget (Government Statements): Interest payable to UK
targeted - Tax for Multinationals
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
This section contains details of the government's planned tax changes which
were given in separate announcements from the Inland Revenue, Customs and
Excise and other government departments after the chancellor had made his
publication of the Budget details in the Finance Bill.
MEASURES will be introduced to charge to tax interest payable within
multinational groups to UK companies by non-resident associated companies on
certain loans and other forms of debt as it accrues rather than when it
arises.
The Inland Revenue said in a statement: 'The legislation will apply where
the terms of the financial arrangement are such that, in any 12 month
period, the amount of interest payable may be less than that accruing pro
rata to the lender in the period. These measures will cover all interest
accruing from midnight on March 311993, in relation to such debts.
'The chancellor's intention is to bring the charging to UK tax of such
interest (or equivalent) more closely into line with that accorded by most
of the UK's major trading partners. This will prevent the loss to the
exchequer which results from multinational groups using the differences in
national tax rules in order to defer UK tax liabilities.
'At present, interest is generally chargeable to tax in the UK when it
arises, rather than when it accrues, unless interest is chargeable to tax as
a receipt of a trade. Most of the UK's major trading partners tax all
interest as it accrues to the lender. Since these countries also tend to
give tax relief to a borrower as interest accrues, multinational groups can
take advantage of this difference in tax treatment. Tax relief for the
interest is obtained by the borrower on an accruals basis but the lender
defers his liability to tax on the interest (often for long periods) by
being taxed on an arising basis.
'The proposed legislation will apply only to loans or other relevant
advances from a UK resident company directly or indirectly to a non-resident
associated company. Where a lender can demonstrate both that a main purpose
of the loan was not to obtain a tax advantage and that it would have been
made by an unrelated party acting at arm's length, the legislation will not
apply.
'The provisions will apply to loans and other forms of debt, including deep
discount securities and deep gain securities , where all or part of the
accruing interest or equivalent becomes payable at intervals in excess of 12
months by being compounded for periods of more than 12 months , rescheduled
or otherwise deferred.
'Interest accruing to the lender in an accounting period in respect of loans
or other forms of debt covered by this proposed legislation will be treated
(to the extent that it is not otherwise already chargeable) as if it had
arisen during that accounting period, rather than in the later accounting
period in which it actually arises.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
