<HEADLINE>
FT  17 MAR 93 / The Budget (Analysis): Tackling the 'surplus' problem -
Advance Corporation Tax
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TONY ALLEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE immediate impact of the change in Advance Corporation Tax will be to cut
the ACT paid on a dividend of Pounds 100 from the present Pounds 33.3 to
Pounds 26.87 in 1993-94 and to Pounds 23.35 in the tax year beginning in
April 1994.
Companies which pay dividends out of UK profits will not be significantly
affected by these changes.
The major change will be to those companies which pay dividends out of
profits they have earned outside the UK. Until now those companies have had
to pay ACT on those dividends, but since they have had no UK corporation tax
to pay on them - because in most cases they will be fully taxed in the
country where they were earned - they cannot offset them. Since ACT is not
repayable, the surplus ACT is effectively a dividend tax.
It is now proposed that dividends paid out of foreign profits - a foreign
income dividend, or FID - will still carry an ACT burden, but that ACT will
now be recoverable from the Inland Revenue if the company cannot offset it
against UK profits. This will be of great help to these companies, and will
significantly reduce their tax burden.
A consultative document will be issued on this proposal. This means that the
relief will not be introduced this year, and also implies that nothing is
being done to enable the many companies affected to recover the surplus ACT
they have already paid.
It may not be of benefit to all their shareholders however. A UK tax payer
will be deemed to have paid income tax at 20 per cent on FIDs. Basic rate
taxpayers will pay no more tax on FIDs. Higher rate UK tax payers will pay
an additional 20 per cent tax.
However, the deemed income tax will not be available for repayment to
non-taxpayers, such as pension funds, nor to overseas shareholders who are
currently able to claim a credit from the UK under tax treaties with the UK.
If this plan goes ahead, companies that pay FIDs may find their shares
become less attractive to overseas shareholders.
The existing rules have been a major disincentive to the setting up of
UK-based foreign-owned holding companies, say, to act as regional
headquarters for group companies in Europe. Instead, these companies have
been established elsewhere in Europe, to the detriment of the UK exchequer.
It is proposed that if agreement of the proposals is delayed beyond the end
of 1993, special rules will be introduced in 1994 to cover just those
companies.
In the meantime, the chancellor has moved to close a loophole exploited by
companies which have tried to use their surplus ACT by selling it to other
companies which are able to use it.
The author is a partner at Coopers &amp; Lybrand.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9311 Finance, Taxation, and Monetary Policy.
    P8721 Accounting, Auditing, and Bookkeeping Services.
</IN>
<XX>
